  "prompt": "Which US Senate seats are up for reelection in 2018?",
  "response": "In the **2018 United States Senate elections**, a total of **35 seats** were contested. This included all **33 Class I Senate seats** up for regular election, as well as **2 special elections**. Below is a comprehensive list of the states that had Senate seats up for reelection in 2018:\n\n### **Regular Elections (Class I Seats)**\n1. **Alabama**\n2. **Arizona**\n3. **Arkansas**\n4. **Colorado**\n5. **Delaware**\n6. **Florida**\n7. **Georgia**\n8. **Hawaii**\n9. **Idaho**\n10. **Illinois**\n11. **Indiana**\n12. **Iowa**\n13. **Kansas**\n14. **Kentucky**\n15. **Louisiana**\n16. **Maine**\n17. **Maryland**\n18. **Massachusetts**\n19. **Michigan**\n20. **Minnesota**\n21. **Missouri**\n22. **Montana**\n23. **Nebraska**\n24. **New Hampshire**\n25. **New York**\n26. **North Carolina**\n27. **North Dakota**\n28. **Ohio**\n29. **Pennsylvania**\n30. **Rhode Island**\n31. **South Carolina**\n32. **South Dakota**\n33. **Texas**\n34. **Utah**\n\n### **Special Elections**\n1. **Alaska**\n   - **Reason:** Incumbent Senator Mark Begich (D) resigned to become Ambassador to Denmark.\n   - **Outcome:** Dan Sullivan (R) won the seat.\n   \n2. **Mississippi**\n   - **Reason:** Incumbent Senator Thad Cochran (R) resigned.\n   - **Outcome:** Cindy Hyde-Smith (R) won the special election.\n\n3. **Tennessee**\n   - **Reason:** Incumbent Senator Bob Corker (R) resigned.\n   - **Outcome:** Marsha Blackburn (R) won the seat.\n\n### **Notable Races and Outcomes**\n- **Arizona:** Incumbent Jeff Flake (R) retired. Democrat Kyrsten Sinema won the seat, flipping it from Republican to Democratic control.\n- **Georgia:** Incumbent Johnny Isakson (R) retired. Republican Kelly Loeffler was appointed but was defeated by Democrat Raphael Warnock in a runoff, flipping the seat to Democratic control.\n- **Mississippi:** The special election was notably competitive, with Cindy Hyde-Smith (R) securing a victory.\n\n### **Overall Impact**\nThe 2018 Senate elections were particularly significant as they determined control of the U.S. Senate. The Democratic Party gained a majority by flipping several seats, which had substantial implications for the legislative agenda and the confirmation of judicial and executive appointments.\n\n### **Summary**\n- **Total Seats Contested:** 35\n  - **Regular Elections (Class I):** 33\n  - **Special Elections:** 2\n\nThese elections played a crucial role in shaping the legislative landscape of the United States during that period.",
